name: liquid packaging board production | turpentine | Cutoff, S
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/27118/documentation

The data set presented is designed as a gate-to-gate data set for LPB. It represents the production of 1000 kg liquid packaging board as used for the production of beverage cartons. Data are based on the average production process of the main European LPB producers.

From reception of raw materials and energy at the factory gate From cradle, i.e. including all upstream activities.

This activity ends with the produced LPB leaving the factory gates before loading the products on lorries or ships. The dataset includes all production steps at the mill including on-site electricity production from the burning of black liquor. The dataset does not include production of machinery/infrastructure.
category: C:Manufacturing/17:Manufacture of paper and paper products/170:Manufacture of paper and paper products/1702:Manufacture of corrugated paper and paperboard and of containers of paper a

processDocumentation.geographyDescription: Data collected from the 4 main European mills that produce more than 95% of European LPB production volume. The data can be considered as representative for European and also Global production.
processDocumentation.samplingDescription:
unweighted average (not weighted according to production volumes for reasons of confidentiality): all four sites belong to only two companies, production volumes are similar between sites though.

Water inputs and outputs: The water output flows from the prechains are not differentiated according to the type of use or if the water is released into a different drainage. Therefore, the overall water consumption cannot be determined. The amount of water evaporated at mill sites in Sweden and Finland and the water in product has been provided by BillerudKorsnäs and Stora Enso: • Evaporated water = 1.57 m³/t LPB (see output flow “[water [air/unspecified]”) • Water in product = 0.07 m³/t LPB All water inputs at mill site are surface water and all water not evaporated or included in products are released back into the same water basin and therefore not consumed.
